    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Cheney for Vice President? Some Early Reviews</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Ken Whelan letter disputes assertion in David Frum's July 25 Op-Ed article that Gov George Bush's choice of Dick Cheney as running mate signals end of Reagan conservatism</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Republicans' Cheney Moment'' (Op-Ed, July 25):</p>
        <p>David Frum interprets the Reagan revolution too narrowly. The Reagan revolution was not the substitution of one set of policies for another; it was a shift in the general philosophy of the country, because Ronald Reagan won over the soul of its people, just as Franklin D. Roosevelt won over the soul of its people during the Depression and World War II.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Republicans' Cheney Moment'' (Op-Ed, July 25):</p>
        <p>David Frum interprets the Reagan revolution too narrowly. The Reagan revolution was not the substitution of one set of policies for another; it was a shift in the general philosophy of the country, because Ronald Reagan won over the soul of its people, just as Franklin D. Roosevelt won over the soul of its people during the Depression and World War II.</p>
        <p>Both presidents got the country to accept a new order of things, which in the case of Roosevelt lined up left of center and in the case of Reagan, right of center. Thus, Democrats who were disillusioned with the welfare state and the federal bureaucracy moved to the right, so that both parties now carry on the Reagan legacy under the rubric of New Democrats and New Republicans. This will continue for the foreseeable future.</p>
        <p>KEN WHELAN  San Francisco, July 25, 2000</p>
      </block>
